  "questions": [
    {
      "question": "A polynomial $p(x)$ of degree $3$ has a graph that intersects the $x$-axis at exactly two distinct points. If one of the zeros is $x = 0$ and the graph is tangent to the $x$-axis at the point $(2, 0)$, write the polynomial $p(x)$ in terms of a constant $k$ and verify the number of zeros.",
      "answer": "$p(x) = k(x^3 - 4x^2 + 4x)$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Since the graph intersects at $x=0$, $(x-0)$ or $x$ is a factor. Since it is tangent at $x=2$, $(x-2)^2$ is a factor.",
          "The general form is $p(x) = k(x)(x-2)^2$. Expanding this gives $p(x) = k(x)(x^2 - 4x + 4) = k(x^3 - 4x^2 + 4x)$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = k(x)(x-2)^2 \\\\ p(x) = k(x)(x^2 - 4x + 4) \\\\ p(x) = k(x^3 - 4x^2 + 4x)$"
      },
